defs.name: Debug

defs.name: http
defs.docs: Types that map to concepts in HTTP.

defs.name: hyper
defs.docs: Re-exported hyper HTTP library types.

defs.name: header
defs.docs: Reexported Hyper header types.

defs.name: uri
defs.docs: Borrowed and owned string types for absolute URIs.

defs.name: URI
defs.docs: Borrowed string type for absolute URIs.

defs.name: new
defs.docs:
Constructs a new URI from a given string. The URI is assumed to be an
 absolute, well formed URI.

defs.name: segment_count
defs.docs:
Returns the number of segments in the URI. Empty segments, which are
 invalid according to RFC#3986, are not counted.

defs.name: segments
defs.docs:
Returns an iterator over the segments of the path in this URI. Skips
 empty segments.

defs.name: path
defs.docs: Returns the path part of this URI.

defs.name: query
defs.docs:
Returns the query part of this URI without the question mark, if there is
 any.

defs.name: fragment
defs.docs:
Returns the fargment part of this URI without the hash mark, if there is
 any.

defs.name: percent_decode
defs.docs:
Returns a URL-decoded version of the string. If the percent encoded
 values are not valid UTF-8, an `Err` is returned.

defs.name: percent_decode_lossy
defs.docs:
Returns a URL-decoded version of the path. Any invalid UTF-8
 percent-encoded byte sequences will be replaced  U+FFFD, the
 replacement character.

defs.name: percent_encode
defs.docs:
Returns a URL-encoded version of the string. Any characters outside of
 visible ASCII-range are encoded as well as ' ', '"', '#', '<', '>', '`',
 '?', '{', '}', '%', and '/'.

defs.name: as_str
defs.docs: Returns the inner string of this URI.

defs.name: Segments
defs.docs: Iterator over the segments of an absolute URI path. Skips empty segments.

defs.name: Utf8
defs.docs: The segment contained invalid UTF8 characters when percent decoded.

defs.name: BadStart
defs.docs: The segment started with the wrapped invalid character.

defs.name: BadChar
defs.docs: The segment contained the wrapped invalid character.

defs.name: BadEnd
defs.docs: The segment ended with the wrapped invalid character.

defs.name: SegmentError
defs.docs:
Errors which can occur when attempting to interpret a segment string as a
 valid path segment.

defs.name: Cookies
defs.docs: Collection of one or more HTTP cookies.

defs.name: get
defs.docs:
Returns a reference to the `Cookie` inside this container with the name
 `name`. If no such cookie exists, returns `None`.

defs.name: get_private
defs.docs:
Returns a reference to the `Cookie` inside this collection with the name
 `name` and authenticates and decrypts the cookie's value, returning a
 `Cookie` with the decrypted value. If the cookie cannot be found, or the
 cookie fails to authenticate or decrypt, `None` is returned.

defs.name: add
defs.docs: Adds `cookie` to this collection.

defs.name: add_private
defs.docs:
Adds `cookie` to the collection. The cookie's value is encrypted with
 authenticated encryption assuring confidentiality, integrity, and
 authenticity. The cookie can later be retrieved using
 [`get_private`](#method.get_private) and removed using
 [`remove_private`](#method.remove_private).

defs.name: remove
defs.docs:
Removes `cookie` from this collection and generates a "removal" cookies
 to send to the client on response. For correctness, `cookie` must
 contain the same `path` and `domain` as the cookie that was initially
 set. Failure to provide the initual `path` and `domain` will result in
 cookies that are not properly removed.

defs.name: remove_private
defs.docs: Removes the private `cookie` from the collection.

defs.name: iter
defs.docs: Returns an iterator over all of the cookies present in this collection.

defs.name: Method
defs.value: Method::{Get, Put, Post, Delete, Options, Head, Trace, Connect, Patch}
defs.docs: Representation of HTTP methods.

defs.name: supports_payload
defs.docs:
Returns `true` if an HTTP request with the method represented by `self`
 supports a payload.

defs.name: as_str
defs.docs: Returns the string representation of `self`.

defs.name: MediaType
defs.docs: An HTTP media type.

defs.name: source
defs.docs: Storage for the entire media type string.

defs.name: top
defs.docs: The top-level type.

defs.name: sub
defs.docs: The subtype.

defs.name: params
defs.docs: The parameters, if any.

defs.name: new
defs.value: fn <T, S> (top: T, sub: S) -> MediaType
defs.docs:
Creates a new `MediaType` with top-level type `top` and subtype `sub`.
 This should _only_ be used to construct uncommon or custom media types.
 Use an associated constant for everything else.

defs.name: with_params
defs.value: fn <T, S, K, V, P> (top: T, sub: S, ps: P) -> MediaType
defs.docs:
Creates a new `MediaType` with top-level type `top`, subtype `sub`, and
 parameters `ps`. This should _only_ be used to construct uncommon or
 custom media types. Use an associated constant for everything else.

defs.name: top
defs.docs:
Returns the top-level type for this media type. The return type,
 `UncasedStr`, has caseless equality comparison and hashing.

defs.name: sub
defs.docs:
Returns the subtype for this media type. The return type,
 `UncasedStr`, has caseless equality comparison and hashing.

defs.name: specificity
defs.docs:
Returns a `u8` representing how specific the top-level type and subtype
 of this media type are.

defs.name: exact_eq
defs.docs:
Compares `self` with `other` and returns `true` if `self` and `other`
 are exactly equal to eachother, including with respect to their
 parameters.

defs.name: params
defs.value: fn <'a> (&'a self) -> impl Iterator<Item = (&'a str, &'a str)> + 'a
defs.docs:
Returns an iterator over the (key, value) pairs of the media type's
 parameter list. The iterator will be empty if the media type has no
 parameters.

defs.name: ContentType
defs.docs: Representation of HTTP Content-Types.

defs.name: new
defs.value: fn <T, S> (top: T, sub: S) -> ContentType
defs.docs:
Creates a new `ContentType` with top-level type `top` and subtype `sub`.
 This should _only_ be used to construct uncommon or custom content
 types. Use an associated constant for everything else.

defs.name: from_extension
defs.docs:
Returns the Content-Type associated with the extension `ext` if the
 extension is recognized. Not all extensions are recognized. If an
 extensions is not recognized, then this method returns `None`. The
 currently recognized extensions are txt, html, htm, xml, csv, js, css,
 json, png, gif, bmp, jpeg, jpg, webp, svg, pdf, ttf, otf, woff, and
 woff2. Extensions are matched case-insensitively.

defs.name: with_params
defs.value: fn <T, S, K, V, P> (top: T, sub: S, ps: P) -> ContentType
defs.docs:
Creates a new `ContentType` with top-level type `top`, subtype `sub`,
 and parameters `ps`. This should _only_ be used to construct uncommon or
 custom content types. Use an associated constant for everything else.

defs.name: media_type
defs.docs: Borrows the inner `MediaType` of `self`.

defs.name: Informational
defs.docs: Indicates a provisional response: a status code of 1XX.

defs.name: Success
defs.docs: Indicates that a request has succeeded: a status code of 2XX.

defs.name: Redirection
defs.docs:
Indicates that further action needs to be taken by the user agent in
 order to fulfill the request: a status code of 3XX.

defs.name: ClientError
defs.docs:
Intended for cases in which the client seems to have erred: a status
 code of 4XX.

defs.name: ServerError
defs.docs:
Indicates cases in which the server is aware that it has erred or is
 incapable of performing the request: a status code of 5XX.

defs.name: Unknown
defs.docs:
Indicates that the status code is nonstandard and unknown: all other
 status codes.

defs.name: StatusClass
defs.value: StatusClass::{Informational, Success, Redirection, ClientError, ServerError, Unknown}
defs.docs: Enumeration of HTTP status classes.

defs.name: Status
defs.docs: Structure representing an HTTP status: an integer code and a reason phrase.

defs.name: code
defs.docs: The HTTP status code associated with this status.

defs.name: reason
defs.docs: The HTTP reason phrase associated with this status.

defs.name: new
defs.docs:
Creates a new `Status` with `code` and `reason`. This should be _only_
 to construct non-standard HTTP statuses. Use an associated constant for
 standard statuses.

defs.name: class
defs.docs: Returns the class of a given status.

defs.name: raw
defs.docs:
Returns a status from a given status code. If the status code is a
 standard code, then the reason phrase is populated accordingly.
 Otherwise the reason phrase is set to "<unknown code>".

defs.name: Header
defs.docs: Simple representation of an HTTP header.

defs.name: name
defs.docs: The name of the header.

defs.name: value
defs.docs: The value of the header.

defs.name: new
defs.value: fn <'a, 'b, N, V> (name: N, value: V) -> Header<'h>
defs.docs:
Constructs a new header. This method should be used rarely and only for
 non-standard headers. Instead, prefer to use the `Into<Header>`
 implementations of many types, including
 [ContentType](struct.ContentType.html) and all of the headers in
 [http::hyper::header](hyper/header/index.html).

defs.name: name
defs.docs:
Returns the name of this header with casing preserved. To do a
 case-insensitive equality check, use `.name` directly.

defs.name: value
defs.docs: Returns the value of this header.

defs.name: HeaderMap
defs.docs: A collection of headers, mapping a header name to its many ordered values.

defs.name: new
defs.docs: Returns an empty collection.

defs.name: contains
defs.docs: Returns true if `self` contains a header with the name `name`.

defs.name: len
defs.docs: Returns the number of _values_ stored in the map.

defs.name: is_empty
defs.docs:
Returns `true` if there are no headers stored in the map. Otherwise
 returns `false`.

defs.name: get
defs.value: fn <'a> (&'a self, name: &str) -> impl Iterator<Item = &'a str>
defs.docs:
Returns an iterator over all of the values stored in `self` for the
 header with name `name`. The headers are returned in FIFO order.

defs.name: get_one
defs.docs:
Returns the _first_ value stored for the header with name `name` if
 there is one.

defs.name: replace
defs.value: fn <'p, H> (&mut self, header: H) -> bool
defs.docs:
Replace any header that matches the name of `header.name` with `header`.
 If there is no such header in `self`, add `header`. If the matching
 header had multiple values, all of the values are removed, and only the
 value in `header` will remain.

defs.name: replace_raw
defs.value: fn <'a, 'b, N, V> (&mut self, name: N, value: V) -> bool
defs.docs:
A convenience method to replace a header using a raw name and value.
 Aliases `replace(Header::new(name, value))`. Should be used rarely.

defs.name: replace_all
defs.value: fn <'n, 'v, H> (&mut self, name: H, values: Vec<Cow<'v, str>>) -> ()
defs.docs:
Replaces all of the values for a header with name `name` with `values`.
 This a low-level method and should rarely be used.

defs.name: add
defs.docs:
Adds `header` into the map. If a header with `header.name` was
 previously added, that header will have one more value.

defs.name: add_raw
defs.value: fn <'a, 'b, N, V> (&mut self, name: N, value: V) -> ()
defs.docs:
A convenience method to add a header using a raw name and value.
 Aliases `add(Header::new(name, value))`. Should be used rarely.

defs.name: add_all
defs.value: fn <'n, H> (&mut self, name: H, values: &mut Vec<Cow<'h, str>>) -> ()
defs.docs:
Adds all of the values to a header with name `name`. This a low-level
 method and should rarely be used. `values` will be empty when this
 method returns.

defs.name: remove
defs.docs: Remove all of the values for header with name `name`.

defs.name: remove_all
defs.docs:
Removes all of the headers stored in this map and returns a vector
 containing them. Header names are returned in no specific order, but all
 values for a given header name are grouped together, and values are in
 FIFO order.

defs.name: iter
defs.docs:
Returns an iterator over all of the `Header`s stored in the map. Header
 names are returned in no specific order, but all values for a given
 header name are grouped together, and values are in FIFO order.

defs.name: into_iter
defs.docs:
Consumes `self` and returns an iterator over all of the `Header`s stored
 in the map. Header names are returned in no specific order, but all
 values for a given header name are grouped together, and values are in
 FIFO order.

defs.name: QMediaType
defs.docs: A `MediaType` with an associated quality value.

defs.name: weight
defs.docs: Retrieve the weight of the media type, if there is any.

defs.name: weight_or
defs.docs: Retrieve the weight of the media type or a given default value.

defs.name: media_type
defs.docs: Borrow the internal `MediaType`.

defs.name: Accept
defs.docs: The HTTP Accept header.

defs.name: new
defs.docs: Constructs a new `Accept` header from one or more media types.

defs.name: preferred
defs.docs:
Retrieve the client's preferred media type. This method follows [RFC
 7231 5.3.2]. If the list of media types is empty, this method returns a
 media type of any with no quality value: (`*/*`).

defs.name: first
defs.docs: Retrieve the first media type in `self`, if any.

defs.name: iter
defs.docs:
Returns an iterator over all of the (quality) media types in `self`.
 Media types are returned in the order in which they appear in the
 header.

defs.name: media_types
defs.docs:
Returns an iterator over all of the (bare) media types in `self`. Media
 types are returned in the order in which they appear in the header.

defs.name: RawStr
defs.docs: A reference to a string inside of a raw HTTP message.

defs.name: from_str
defs.docs: Constructs an `&RawStr` from an `&str` at no cost.

defs.name: percent_decode
defs.docs: Returns a percent-decoded version of the string.

defs.name: percent_decode_lossy
defs.docs:
Returns a percent-decoded version of the string. Any invalid UTF-8
 percent-encoded byte sequences will be replaced  U+FFFD, the
 replacement character.

defs.name: url_decode
defs.docs:
Returns a URL-decoded version of the string. This is identical to
 percent decoding except that `+` characters are converted into spaces.
 This is the encoding used by form values.

defs.name: html_escape
defs.docs:
Returns an HTML escaped version of `self`. Allocates only when
 characters need to be escaped.

defs.name: as_str
defs.docs: Converts `self` into an `&str`.

defs.name: as_uncased_str
defs.docs: Converts `self` into an `&UncasedStr`.

defs.name: is_indexed
defs.docs: Whether this string is derived from indexes or not.

defs.name: to_str
defs.value: fn <'a> (&'a self, string: Option<&'a str>) -> &'a str
defs.docs:
Retrieves the string `self` corresponds to. If `self` is derived from
 indexes, the corresponding subslice of `string` is returned. Otherwise,
 the concrete string is returned.

defs.name: uncased
defs.docs: Contains types that encapsulate uncased ASCII strings.

defs.name: UncasedStr
defs.docs:
A reference to an uncased (case-preserving) ASCII string. This is typically
 created from an `&str` as follows:

defs.name: new
defs.docs: Returns a reference to an `UncasedStr` from an `&str`.

defs.name: as_str
defs.docs: Returns `self` as an `&str`.

defs.name: into_uncased
defs.docs: Converts a `Box<UncasedStr>` into an `Uncased` without copying or allocating.

defs.name: Uncased
defs.docs: An uncased (case-preserving), owned _or_ borrowed ASCII string.

defs.name: new
defs.docs: Creates a new `Uncased` string from `string` without allocating.

defs.name: into_string
defs.docs: Converts `self` into an owned `String`, allocating if necessary.

defs.name: into_boxed_uncased
defs.docs: Converts `self` into a `Box<UncasedStr>`.

defs.name: into_cow
defs.docs: Returns the inner `Cow`.

defs.name: uncased_eq
defs.value: fn <S1, S2> (s1: S1, s2: S2) -> bool
defs.docs: Returns true if `s1` and `s2` are equal without considering case.

defs.name: request
defs.docs: Types and traits for request parsing and handling.

defs.name: Request
defs.docs: The type of an incoming web request.

defs.name: method
defs.docs: Retrieve the method from `self`.

defs.name: set_method
defs.docs: Set the method of `self`.

defs.name: uri
defs.docs: Borrow the URI from `self`, which is guaranteed to be an absolute URI.

defs.name: set_uri
defs.docs:
Set the URI in `self`. The `uri` parameter can be of any type that
 implements `Into<URI>` including `&str` and `String`; it _must_ be a
 valid, absolute URI.

defs.name: remote
defs.docs:
Returns the address of the remote connection that initiated this
 request if the address is known. If the address is not known, `None` is
 returned.

defs.name: set_remote
defs.docs: Sets the remote address of `self` to `address`.

defs.name: headers
defs.docs:
Returns a [`HeaderMap`](/rocket/http/struct.HeaderMap.html) of all of
 the headers in `self`.

defs.name: add_header
defs.docs:
Add `header` to `self`'s headers. The type of `header` can be any type
 that implements the `Into<Header>` trait. This includes common types
 such as [`ContentType`](/rocket/http/struct.ContentType.html) and
 [`Accept`](/rocket/http/struct.Accept.html).

defs.name: replace_header
defs.docs:
Replaces the value of the header with name `header.name` with
 `header.value`. If no such header exists, `header` is added as a header
 to `self`.

defs.name: cookies
defs.docs: Returns a wrapped borrow to the cookies in `self`.

defs.name: content_type
defs.docs:
Returns the Content-Type header of `self`. If the header is not present,
 returns `None`. The Content-Type header is cached after the first call
 to this function. As a result, subsequent calls will always return the
 same value.

defs.name: accept
defs.docs:
Returns the Accept header of `self`. If the header is not present,
 returns `None`. The Accept header is cached after the first call to this
 function. As a result, subsequent calls will always return the same
 value.

defs.name: format
defs.docs: Returns the media type "format" of the request.

defs.name: limits
defs.docs: Returns the configured application receive limits.

defs.name: route
defs.docs: Get the presently matched route, if any.

defs.name: guard
defs.docs: Invokes the request guard implemention for `T`, returning its outcome.

defs.name: get_param
defs.value: fn <'a, T> (&'a self, n: usize) -> Result<T, Error>
defs.docs:
Retrieves and parses into `T` the 0-indexed `n`th dynamic parameter from
 the request. Returns `Error::NoKey` if `n` is greater than the number of
 params. Returns `Error::BadParse` if the parameter type `T` can't be
 parsed from the parameter.

defs.name: get_param_str
defs.docs:
Get the `n`th path parameter as a string, if it exists. This is used by
 codegen.

defs.name: get_segments
defs.value: fn <'a, T> (&'a self, n: usize) -> Result<T, Error>
defs.docs:
Retrieves and parses into `T` all of the path segments in the request
 URI beginning at the 0-indexed `n`th dynamic parameter. `T` must
 implement [FromSegments](/rocket/request/trait.FromSegments.html), which
 is used to parse the segments.

defs.name: get_raw_segments
defs.docs:
Get the segments beginning at the `n`th dynamic parameter, if they
 exist. Used by codegen.

defs.name: FromParam
defs.docs: Trait to convert a dynamic path segment string to a concrete value.

defs.name: Error
defs.docs: The associated error to be returned when parsing fails.

defs.name: from_param
defs.docs:
Parses an instance of `Self` from a dynamic path parameter string or
 returns an `Error` if one cannot be parsed.

defs.name: FromSegments
defs.docs: Trait to convert _many_ dynamic path segment strings to a concrete value.

defs.name: Error
defs.docs: The associated error to be returned when parsing fails.

defs.name: from_segments
defs.docs:
Parses an instance of `Self` from many dynamic path parameter strings or
 returns an `Error` if one cannot be parsed.

defs.name: FormItems
defs.docs: Iterator over the key/value pairs of a given HTTP form string.

defs.name: completed
defs.docs:
Returns `true` if the form string was parsed to completion. Returns
 `false` otherwise. All valid form strings will parse to completion,
 while invalid form strings will not.

defs.name: exhaust
defs.docs:
Parses all remaining key/value pairs and returns `true` if parsing ran
 to completion. All valid form strings will parse to completion, while
 invalid form strings will not.

defs.name: inner_str
defs.docs:
Retrieves the original string being parsed by this iterator. The string
 returned by this method does not change, regardless of the status of the
 iterator.

defs.name: FromForm
defs.docs:
Trait to create an instance of some type from an HTTP form.
 [Form](struct.Form.html) requires its generic type to implement this trait.

defs.name: Error
defs.docs: The associated error to be returned when parsing fails.

defs.name: from_form
defs.value: fn (it: &mut FormItems<'f>, strict: bool) -> Result<Self, Self::Error>
defs.docs: Parses an instance of `Self` from the iterator of form items `it`.

defs.name: FromFormValue
defs.docs:
Trait to create instance of some type from a form value; expected from field
 types in structs deriving `FromForm`.

defs.name: Error
defs.docs:
The associated error which can be returned from parsing. It is a good
 idea to have the return type be or contain an `&'v str` so that the
 unparseable string can be examined after a bad parse.

defs.name: from_form_value
defs.docs:
Parses an instance of `Self` from an HTTP form field value or returns an
 `Error` if one cannot be parsed.

defs.name: default
defs.docs:
Returns a default value to be used when the form field does not exist.
 If this returns `None`, then the field is required. Otherwise, this
 should return `Some(default_value)`. The default implementation simply
 returns `None`.

defs.name: Form

defs.name: to
defs.docs:
Construct a temporary "see other" (303) redirect response. This is the
 typical response when redirecting a user to another page. This type of
 redirect indicates that the client should look elsewhere, but always via
 a `GET` request, for a given resource.

defs.name: temporary
defs.docs:
Construct a "temporary" (307) redirect response. This response instructs
 the client to reissue the current request to a different URL,
 maintaining the contents of the request identically. This means that,
 for example, a `POST` request will be resent, contents included, to the
 requested URL.

defs.name: permanent
defs.docs:
Construct a "permanent" (308) redirect response. This redirect must only
 be used for permanent redirects as it is cached by clients. This
 response instructs the client to reissue requests for the current URL to
 a different URL, now and in the future, maintaining the contents of the
 request identically. This means that, for example, a `POST` request will
 be resent, contents included, to the requested URL.

defs.name: found
defs.docs:
Construct a temporary "found" (302) redirect response. This response
 instructs the client to reissue the current request to a different URL,
 ideally maintaining the contents of the request identically.
 Unfortunately, different clients may respond differently to this type of
 redirect, so `303` or `307` redirects, which disambiguate, are
 preferred.

defs.name: moved
defs.docs:
Construct a permanent "moved" (301) redirect response. This response
 should only be used for permanent redirects as it can be cached by
 browsers. Because different clients may respond differently to this type
 of redirect, a `308` redirect, which disambiguates, is preferred.

defs.name: merge
defs.docs:
Merges the `other` `Response` into `self` by setting any fields in
 `self` to the corresponding value in `other` if they are set in `other`.
 Fields in `self` are unchanged if they are not set in `other`. If a

defs.name: join
defs.docs:

 both `self` and `other`, the values are adjoined, with the values in
 `self` coming first. Headers only in `self` or `other` are set in

defs.docs:

 ignored. Any environment variables setting config parameters are
 ignored. If `log` is `true`, logging is enabled.

 available at `base/path`.
